SUMMARIZE Section
1. Constant Line
Meaning: A straight horizontal or vertical line at a fixed value.
 Use: Show benchmark, target value, minimum performance level.
 Example: Add a constant line at ₹50,000 Sales target.
 Exercise:
Create a bar chart of Category vs Sales
Drag Constant Line → Pane
Type 50000 as target
Ask students to highlight categories above/below target.
Average Line
Meaning: Shows the average of a measure across the view.
 Use: Quickly understand performance above/below average.
 Example: Add Average Profit line on a scatter chart.
 Exercise:
Scatter: Sales vs Profit
Drag Average Line → Table
Students identify points below average profit.
 Median with Quartiles
Meaning: Shows median (50th percentile) + quartiles (Q1 25%, Q3 75%).
 Use: Understand distribution, detect skewness.
 Example: Sales distribution of products (Box-like distribution).
 Exercise:
Create histogram of Sales
Add Median with Quartiles
Students identify skewness (right/left skew).
Box Plot
Meaning: A statistical chart showing minimum, Q1, median, Q3, maximum, and outliers.
 Use: Spot outliers, distribution spread.
 Example: Compare discount distribution across categories.
 Exercise:
Drag Category → Columns, Discount → Rows
Add Box Plot from Analytics pane
Students explain which category has most outliers.
Totals
Meaning: Adds row total, column total, grand total.
 Use: Performance summary.
 Example: Show grand total of Sales in a table.
 Exercise:
Create a crosstab: Category vs Subcategory → Sales
Analytics → Totals → Show Row/Column/Grand Totals
Ask: Which category contributes most to total?
MODEL Section
6. Average with 95% CI (Confidence Interval)
Meaning: Shows average + range where true mean lies with 95% confidence.
 Use: Statistical reliability, compare group means.
 Example: Avg Sales of different categories with CI.
 Exercise:
Category vs Sales bar chart
Add Average with 95% CI
Students explain if confidence intervals overlap.
Median with 95% CI
Meaning: Same as above but based on median instead of mean.
 Use: For skewed data or outliers.
 Example: Order processing time distribution.
 Exercise:
Create distribution chart of Delivery Days
Add Median with 95% CI
Ask: Which categories have wide CI (unstable performance)?
Trend Line
Meaning: Shows trend pattern (linear, exponential, polynomial).
 Use: Predict future direction (increasing/decreasing).
 Example: Show sales growth over months.
 Exercise:
Line chart: Month vs Sales
Drag Trend Line → Linear
Students check if R² is high or low (strength of trend).
Forecast
Meaning: Uses historical data to predict future values.
 Use: Time-series forecasting for sales, revenue, customers.
 Example: Forecast next 12 months sales.
 Exercise:
Month vs Sales
Drag Forecast → Pane
Students explain forecast summary (upper/lower bounds).
Cluster
Meaning: Groups similar data points into clusters using k-means algorithm.
 Use: Customer segmentation, product segmentation.
 Example: Segment customers based on Sales vs Profit.
 Exercise:
Scatter: Sales vs Profit
Drag Cluster → View
Try 3–5 clusters
Students label clusters: “High Value”, “Medium Value”, “Low Value”.
CUSTOM Section
11. Reference Line
Meaning: Add dynamic line based on measure (mean, sum, min, max, fixed value).
 Use: Highlight metric target or threshold.
 Example: Add reference line for Average Sales.
 Exercise:
Bar chart → add Reference Line (SUM of Sales)
Students customize label (value + percent).
Reference Band
Meaning: Highlight a shaded band between two values.
 Use: Show acceptable range or tolerance zone.
 Example: Highlight profit range between 5% to 10%.
 Exercise:
Drag Reference Band → Pane
Set “min 1000” to “max 5000”
Students adjust shading color.
Distribution Band
Meaning: Shows distribution ranges like percentiles or standard deviations.
 Use: Statistical spread visualized as bands.
 Example: ±1 Standard Deviation band on sales chart.
 Exercise:
Create line chart
Add Distribution Band (Std Dev = 1, 2)
Students explain if data is stable or variable.
Box Plot (again under Custom)
Meaning: Same as Summarize but more customizable.
 Use: Use custom box plot when you want:
 ✔ Change whisker computation
 ✔ Add color
 ✔ Add labels
 ✔ Use for specific dimensions
 Example: Department-wise salary distribution.
 Exercise:
Use Custom Box Plot
Modify inner quartile range
Compare with the automatic box plot.
