Tableau Relationships: Logical Table Connections for Smart Visualizations:

Definition:
In Tableau, a relationship is a logical connection established between two or more tables without physically merging them. This means the tables remain in their original form, and Tableau joins them at query time when needed.

Purpose:
To combine data from multiple tables.
To avoid data duplication.
To improve query performance, as the tables are not physically merged—only a logical connection exists.
Key Points:
Relationships exist in the logical layer, not the physical join layer.
Tableau automatically determines the join type (Left, Inner, etc.) based on the visualization.
Relationships are flexible, combining data according to conditions set in the visualization.

Feature
Relationship
Join (Physical)
Data Storage
Tables remain in original form (Logical Layer)
Tables are physically merged into a new, single table
Data Duplication
Avoids duplication
Can cause duplication (if join is one-to-many)
Query Timing
On-demand (Tableau determines join type at the time of visualization)
Merged immediately (fixed join type: Inner, Left, Right, Full)
Performance
Generally better for large, complex datasets and multi-table analysis
Can be heavy and slow down data source loading if not optimized
Flexibility
High (join type adapts dynamically)
Limited (fixed join type, must be manually specified)
Complexity
Simpler to set up (Just match fields)
Requires understanding of join types (Inner, Left, etc.)

When to Use Relationships
When you have multiple fact tables or dimension tables and want to avoid data duplication.
When your visualization requires combining data at different granularities (levels of detail).
For large datasets where physical joins might slow performance.

Logical Layer (Relationship): Step drag and drop .
It is a logical connection, tables are not physically merged.
Data remains in its original form.













Physical Layer (Join / Union):

It is a physical connection, tables are merged into a new table.
The merge happens immediately, ready for visualization.
For large datasets, performance can sometimes slow down.
Example: Inner Join, Left Join, Right Join, Full Outer Join in Tableau.













Inner Join:
Definition: Returns only the records that match in both tables.
Example:
Sales Table: OrderID, CustomerID, Amount
Customer Table: CustomerID, CustomerName
Result: Only customers who have sales appear in the output.
2️⃣ Left Join
Definition: Returns all records from the left table and the matching records from the right table. If no match, right table fields are NULL.


Example:
Left Table (Customer): CustomerID, CustomerName
Right Table (Sales): CustomerID, Amount
Result: All customers are listed, even if they have no sales. Sales Amount will be NULL for customers without sales.
3️⃣ Right Join
Definition: Returns all records from the right table and the matching records from the left table. If no match, left table fields are NULL.
Example:
Right Table (Sales): OrderID, CustomerID, Amount
Left Table (Customer): CustomerID, CustomerName
Result: All sales records are included, even if the customer info is missing. CustomerName will be NULL if no matching customer exists.


4️⃣ Full Outer Join
Definition: Returns all records from both tables, with NULLs where there is no match.
Example:
Combines all customers and all sales.
If a customer has no sales → Amount = NULL.
If a sale has no customer info → CustomerName = NULL.
Quick Visualization Concept:
Inner Join → Intersection of both tables
Left Join  → All left + matching right
Right Join → All right + matching left
Full Outer → Everything from both tables

All Charts In Tableau

Text Table (Crosstab) in Tableau – 
Meaning
A Text Table (Crosstab) displays data in rows and columns, similar to an Excel Pivot Table.
 It shows exact numbers instead of charts.
🔹 Usage
Comparing values across multiple categories
MIS / tabular reporting
Category–Subcategory comparison
Showing key metrics together (Sales, Profit, Discount, etc.)


















Bar Chart:
Usage:
Compare values across categories


Easy to find highest & lowest
Superstore Example:
Profit by Segment & Category.
















Heat Map
Usage:
Color intensity comparison


Quickly finds high/low performance areas
Example:
Category & Sub-category Profit Heat Map.

Profit Ratio
Shows how much profit is earned per dollar of sales.
Formula:
[Profit] / [Sales]




















Discount % (Correct Calculation):
Usage
Shows true discount%, not total discount.
AVG([Discount])


